SimpleCTF

Target IP: 10.10.17.76
Challenge Description: Beginner level ctf.

Reconnaissance


Performing a port scan using the command sudo nmap -sS 10.10.17.76 -p- shows there are three TCP ports open on the target machine, as shown above. They are FTP, HTTP, and another application on port 2222. Time to identify the different services & applications using an aggressive scan.


I performed an aggressive scan using the command sudo nmap -sV -A 10.10.17.76 -p 21,80,2222 and obtained the result shown above. The target machine seems to be running VSFTPD 3.0.3 FTP application on port 21, Apache 2.4.18 web server on port 80, and OpenSSH 7.2p2 SSH application on port 2222. I notice it is possible to login as anonymous via the FTP. However, there is a timeout while trying to obtain the directory. I will enumerate the HTTP application on port 80 first. The scan above found the interesting entry /openemr-5_0_1_3 inside the robots.txt. Maybe it is worth investigating.

Enumeration

Port 80: HTTP

The default Apache webpage shown above is displayed for this application on port 80. I viewed the source-code of the webpage but I did not find anything useful, such as hardcoded credentials and developer comments. I browsed to /openemr-5_0_1_3 directory but I did not find anything either. Time to perform a directory search.


I performed a directory search using the command gobuster dir -u http://10.10.17.76 -w /usr/share/wordlists/dirbuster/directory-list-2.3-medium.txt -x html,php,txt and obtained the result shown above. There is an interesting directory with the name /simple.


I browsed to http://10.10.17.76/simple/ and obtained the webpage shown above. The target machine seems to be running Simple CMS here. Reading through the source code of the webpage, I obtained the application version 2.2.8. From past experience, I know it is vulnerable to SQL injection.

Exploitation


Doing a Google search for Simple 2.2.8 vulnerabilities lead me to the exploit shown above. This CVE has the ID of CVE-2019-9053. I downloaded a copy of the exploit on my machine and renamed the file to exp.py. I had to fix the exploit code as it was outdated.


Running the exploit using the command python3 exp.py -u http://10.10.17.76/simple --crack -w /usr/share/wordlists/rockyou.txt returns the problem shown above. I managed to obtain the salt and password hash for the username mitch. Maybe I can create a Python script to crack the password hash via bruteforce. I did a Google search for 0c01f4468bd75d7a84c7eb73846e8d96 and obtained the result secret.


From directory search against the /simple, I identified another directory with the name /admin. Browsing to this directory leads to the webpage shown above. I can try to login with the new credentials.


And bingo! I successfully logged into the web application with the credentials mitch:secret. Now I have access to the CMS as the user mitch, as shown above. There are multiple attack vectors I can use now. I can try to upload a webshell to obtain an RCE. However, there are SSH applications, for example on port 2222, from previous enumeration -- maybe I can test the credentials mitch:secret there too?


And wow. I managed to SSH into the target machine using the credentials. Now I have a foothold on the target machine as the user mitch, as shown above. Time to escalate my privileges to root.

Privilege Escalation


Since I have the password of the user mitch. I ran the command sudo -l and obtained the entry (root) NOPASSWD: /usr/bin/vim. This means I can execute the binary /usr/bin/vim with sudo privileges. GG. To obtain a root shell, I executed the command sudo vim -c ':!/bin/sh'. Now I have a root shell on the target machine, as shown above.
